`menuModal.hide();` is [asynchronous](https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.1/components/modal/#hide), you could try listening to the `hidden.bs.modal` event on `menuModal` and then call `displayModeSetting.show()` from there.

Something like:
```js
function showDisplayModeSettings() {
  const displayModeSetting = bootstrap.Modal.getOrCreateInstance(document.getElementById('displayModeSetting'));
  const alreadyOpen = document.querySelector('.modal.show');
  if (alreadyOpen) {
    alreadyOpen.addEventListener('hidden.bs.modal', () => { displayModeSetting.show(); }, { once: true })
    bootstrap.Modal.getOrCreateInstance(alreadyOpen).hide();
  } else {
    displayModeSetting.show();
  }
}
```

> I have a use-case of wanting to apply `text-truncate` styles to an existing class. It is safer for me to extend the Bootstrap utility, knowing that if something is fixed in the future regarding how to handle text ellipsis, the fix will be applied to my code as well.

Regarding your use case: as far as I see `.text-truncate` only uses the `text-truncate` mixin (at least as of Bootstrap v5.1.3). So you could just use the mixin as well.
Generally talking about Bootstrap utility classes generated via the Bootstrap Utility API, one should be able to extend from them just fine - as they should not be nested into some other contexts.

The issue comes up when a class e.g. `.fw-bold` is changed in nested structures and extended from:
```scss
.component1 {
	.fw-bold { // we want bold text in this class to be red as well
		text-color: red;
	}
}

.component2 { // we want text in this class to be black
	@extend .fw-bold;
}
```

it results in the following CSS:
```css
.fw-bold, .component2 {
  font-weight: bold;
}
.component1 .fw-bold, .component1 .component2 {
  text-color: red;
}
```

Here the selector ".component1 .component2" is generated which we probably did not want here.
As I said, the example above – modifying a utility class in nested structures – is obviously bad practice and shouldn't be the case with Bootstrap core. So it _should_ be fine to extend Bootstrap Utility classes.

