One way to implement this feature would be to add a new customClasses option to the Backdrop class, which would accept an array of strings representing the class names to be added to the backdrop element. You could then use this option to specify the custom classes when creating a new instance of the Backdrop class:
class Backdrop {
  // ...

  constructor(config) {
    this._config = config;
  }

  // ...
}

return new Backdrop({
  isVisible: Boolean(this._config.backdrop), // 'static' option will be translated to true, and booleans will keep their value,
  isAnimated: () => this._isAnimated(),
  customClasses: ['bg-transparent']
});
You would then need to update the Backdrop class to add the specified custom classes to the backdrop element when it is inserted into the DOM. This could be done using the classList.add() method:
class Backdrop {
  // ...

  _insertElement() {
    // ...

    this._element.classList.add(...this._config.customClasses);
  }
}

