Again this might be edge case for most people, but for my software, people can switch between RTL and LTR languages instantly. or in other words they are both available at the same time (most of the time element level)

With this, I cannot link both RTL and LTR css files at the same time, since they conflict.

Instead, I combine `bootstrap.css` and `bootstrap.rtl.css` to one single file, ignoring classes that are similar between RTL and LTR
next I add `[dir="rtl"]` infront of classes that are meant for RTL overriding those properties that are different.

```css
.me-auto{ margin-right:auto !important; }
[dir="rtl"] .me-auto{ margin-left:auto !important; margin-right:unset !important; }

.ms-auto{ margin-left:auto !important; }
[dir="rtl"] .ms-auto{ margin-left:unset !important; margin-right:auto !important; }

.text-start { text-align: left !important; }
[dir="rtl"] .text-start { text-align: right !important; }

.text-end { text-align: right !important; }
[dir="rtl"] .text-end { text-align: left !important; }

...

/*These classes are needed for hard left and right ( number, date and code container elements) */
.ml-auto{ margin-left:auto !important; }
.mr-auto{ margin-right:auto !important; }

.text-left { text-align: left !important; }
.text-right { text-align: right !important; }

...
```

This is until chrome, edge and opera too start supporting `:dir(LTR)` and `:dir(RTL)` at that time, those classes will be simpler and I don't need to unset the opposite property

```css
.me-auto:dir(ltr){ margin-right:auto !important; }
.me-auto:dir(rtl){ margin-left:auto !important; }
.ms-auto:dir(ltr){ margin-left:auto !important; }
.ms-auto:dir(rtl){{ margin-right:auto !important; }
...
```

Since changing from LTR to RTL just need adding an attribute to HTML tag in most cases (it immediately changes direction)
in some other cases (e.g. posting to forum) it is applied to root element of form using a button and everything works fine in both direction. User can switch between two modes by clicking that button and continue preparing their post in their desired language. and when retrieving a text content from server, I just need to set the direction on root of element and I'm good to go, without worrying if it will show codes, numbers and dates in wrong direction (I fix them using `text-left` and `text-right` instead of `text-end` and `text-start`)

