@lekoala Thanks very much! I came across the `IntersectionObserver` API when trying to find a solution for lazy-loading, but it looked very complicated as I am not a web-developer. But you're right that it was fairly easy to implement and it works great!

Here's my solution that may perhaps help others in the future:

    <script>
    /** Setup event-handler to lazy-load HTML elements, also inside nested tabs.
      * This registers all the HTML elements with an IntersectionObserver, which
      * triggers an event whenever the element becomes visible to the user,
      * so the element's contents can be lazy-loaded.
      */
    function setupHandlerLazy() {
      // Create a new observer object that triggers when elements become visible.
      const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
        entries.forEach((entry) => {
          if (entry.intersectionRatio > 0) {
            // Element became visible to the user.

            // Get the HTML ID for the lazy element.
            var lazy_id = entry.target.id;
            
            // Does the HTML ID exist?
            if (lazy_id) {
              // AJAX lazy-loading of the element. (Function not shown here.)
              ajaxLazy(id=lazy_id);
            }
          }
        });
      });

      // Register the HTML elements that need lazy-loading.
      document.querySelectorAll("div.lazy").forEach((element) => {
        observer.observe(element);
      });
    }
    </script>

As this solves my problem, I currently don't have any need for propagating `shown.bs.tab` events anymore, so I have closed this issue.

