Hey there,
I recognize that you're looking for an option to manually enable dark mode using Bootstrap's "class" strategy, in a way that is similar to what Tailwind CSS provides.
At the moment, Bootstrap doesn't come with a built-in feature to manually enable dark mode using a class strategy. However, you can accomplish a similar feature by combining JavaScript and customized CSS.
To provide this functionality, one approach is to use an HTML tag's data attribute to toggle between light and dark mode. Here is an illustration of its use:
Add the following CSS to your custom stylesheet:
/* Default to light mode */
body {
    background-color: #fff;
    color: #000;
}
/* Dark mode styles */
[data-bs-theme="dark"] body {
    background-color: #222;
    color: #fff;
}
Add a data attribute to the HTML tag, as follows:
<html data-bs-theme="light">
Use JavaScript to toggle the data attribute when a user clicks a button or switch to enable dark mode. Here is an example using jQuery:
javascript
$('.btn-toggle-dark-mode').click(function() {
    $('html').attr('data-bs-theme', 'dark');
});
Add the 'dark-mode' class to any elements that you want to style differently in dark mode. Here is an example:
<div class="bg-white dark-mode:bg-dark">
  <!-- ... -->
</div>
With this implementation, the data attribute on the HTML tag will change to 'data-bs-theme="dark"' when the user clicks the button or switch to enable dark mode, triggering the dark mode styles specified in the custom stylesheet. The background color and other styles of elements with the 'dark-mode' class will be adjusted accordingly.
I hope this would be useful.

