To solve this issue, one possible solution is to adjust the dismiss button's padding using the same CSS property. You can achieve this by adding the following CSS rule to your stylesheet:
.alert-dismissible .btn-close {
    --bs-alert-padding-y: var(--bs-alert-padding-y);
    --bs-alert-padding-x: var(--bs-alert-padding-x);
}
This rule sets the --bs-alert-padding-y and --bs-alert-padding-x variables of the dismiss button to the same values as the alert's padding, which ensures consistent sizing.

Alternatively, you could use the calc() function to adjust the dismiss button's padding based on the alert's padding, like so:
.alert-dismissible .btn-close {
    padding-top: calc(var(--bs-alert-padding-y) - 0.5rem);
    padding-right: calc(var(--bs-alert-padding-x) - 0.5rem);
    padding-bottom: calc(var(--bs-alert-padding-y) - 0.5rem);
    padding-left: calc(var(--bs-alert-padding-x) - 0.5rem);
}
This rule subtracts 0.5rem from the alert's padding to get the dismiss button's padding, which should maintain consistent sizing.

